<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Whistleblower Award FAQ</h1>

  <h2>Who qualifies for a whistleblower award?</h2>
  <p>You must voluntarily provide original information about violations to the relevant agency. "Original information" means information not already known to the agency from another source, derived from your independent knowledge or analysis.</p>

  <h2>Can I report anonymously and still receive an award?</h2>
  <p>For SEC and CFTC programs, you can submit anonymously if represented by an attorney. You must reveal your identity before collecting an award. IRS and FCA programs generally require identification upfront.</p>

  <h2>What anti-retaliation protections exist?</h2>
  <p>All major programs include anti-retaliation protections. The SEC Whistleblower Program protects employees from termination, demotion, or harassment for reporting. Remedies include reinstatement, double back pay, and attorney fees under Dodd-Frank Section 21F.</p>

  <h2>How long does the award process take?</h2>
  <p>SEC cases take an average of 4–7 years from tip submission to award. Investigations are lengthy and awards are paid only after sanctions are collected. Patience is essential.</p>

  <h2>What is a False Claims Act qui tam suit?</h2>
  <p>A qui tam suit is a lawsuit filed by a private individual (relator) on behalf of the government against contractors who defrauded the government. The government may intervene and take over the case, or the relator may proceed alone. Awards range from 15%–30% of government recoveries.</p>

  <h2>Does reporting internally first protect or hurt my award?</h2>
  <p>For SEC/CFTC, internal reporting can be credited as a positive factor if the company later reports to the SEC, preserving your status as an original source. However, internal reporting that allows the company to destroy evidence is harmful. Consult a whistleblower attorney before deciding.</p>
</BaseLayout>
